cess in digital entrepreneurship: passivity in decision-making, hierarchical compliance, and zero autonomy over business outcomes. As a founder and creator, you control your narrative, iterate your strategy daily, and capture the upside of your effort and innovation. As a pilot, you execute predetermined procedures, follow air traffic control directives, and operate within rigid FAA regulations and union contracts. Your compensation is fixed and predictable—which sounds appealing until you realize it means your upside is capped. You don't build equity in anything except a pension. The timeline is also brutal. Your SaaS ventures, digital products, and content businesses likely took 2-4 years to generate meaningful revenue. You're asking to trade 3+ years of your 30s/40s (pilot training pipeline) for a salary job that begins at $110K. During those training years, you'll be unable to grow your existing ventures, likely generating zero new revenue from them. The psychological mismatch: Digital entrepreneurs are conditioned to optimize, innovate, and challenge status quo. Aviation is the opposite—it's one of the few industries where doing things exactly as mandated (standard operating procedures) is the entire point. This isn't a feature; it's a requirement for safety. Many career-switchers find this deeply unsatisfying after 18-24 months. REFRAMED QUESTION YOU SHOULD ASK YOURSELF Are you asking this because: You want to escape the grind of entrepreneurship? (Legitimate, but pilot training + early career might be more grinding) You need more stable income immediately? (Better options exist that don't require 3+ years of training) You're genuinely fascinated by aviation itself? (Only valid reason to make this move) You're seeking a \"backup plan\" income source? (Then this is the wrong move—it requires full commitment) ALTERNATIVE PIVOT OPTIONS WITH BETTER ROI FOR YOUR SKILLS If stability + income are the drivers, consider these paths that leverage your existing expertise and require months, not years: Commercial Aviation Content Creator: Position yourself as the digital marketing authority for aviation companies. Pilot training programs, avionics manufacturers, and flight schools desperately need content creators who understand both marketing and aviation. EdTech Founder (Aviation Focus): Build a course, software, or platform that serves the 20,000+ aspiring pilots annually. Your SaaS + content skills are directly applicable. Consulting for Aviation Startups: Startup air taxi services, pilot training platforms, and aviation tech companies need someone who can build digital products and manage growth. These paths preserve your income-generating capacity while building on demonstrated strengths, rather than starting from zero in a field where your competitive advantage is minimal. IF YOU DECIDE TO PROCEED: Delta Propel MGA Tactical SOP Stage\tAction\tTimeline\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tCost/Resource Required\tSuccess Metric 1. Eligibility Verification\tConfirm you meet basic requirements: First Class Medical, valid passport, no felonies/DUI\t2-4 weeks\tOriginal medical records, passport\tFAA First Class Medical Certificate\t$150-300 (medical exam)\tApproved First Class Medical 2. Flight Time Foundation\tIf you have zero flight hours, complete Private Pilot Certificate at local flight school\t3-6 months\t$10,000-15,000 flight time cost\t40-60 flight hours + Private Pilot rating\t$10K-15K + time commitment\tPrivate Pilot Certificate issued 3. Enrollment in MGA Program\tContact MGA Aviation department; confirm you meet collegiate pathway requirements (4-year program or 2-year + additional prerequisites)\t1-2 months\tHigh school transcripts, existing college credits, application materials\tAcceptance to MGA Bachelor of Science in Aviation Science & Management, Flight\t$40K-80K total program cost\tAdmission acceptance letter from MGA 4. Propel Application (Year 3)\tAfter 1.5-2 years of coursework, submit Propel QJO application; inc